Hardware Manufacturer Policies for Compatibility
text:
Hello Everyone!

I was wonder about the EU - USB-C policies and thinking about where could people submit or suggest ideas regarding this kind of policies. It may would consider in the US in the Right to Repair movement or in the EU (I am not sure exactly yet). In case you know, please share. I know, it's not a big deal to google it, but I would be happy to hear your ideas and opinion as well, here is mine.

My idea is to don't let HW manufacturers to give a limit of unsing PCIe devices. I seriously believe it creates a huge amount of e-waste. Laptop manufacturers limit wifi modules to be able to use only the ones sold with the product, workstation manufacturers limit video cards etc. It is a poisonous practice and if USB-C can be forced on a phone.... It should be an easy move to don't let manufacturers to take effort to keep their products NOT being upgradable.

I am not sure if any policy is already on the way. I think it would deserve to take effort for, and would make a change for sustainability. Other way HW manufacturers will keep producing waste and limit their product's usability for the continuous success of their future products.

Stripe account suffered a card test
text:
My Stripe account suffered a card test, Stripe asked me to provide KYB materials including inventory documents and company documents, shipping information, but the account was still closed and Stripe is about to make a mandatory refund of all funds in the account (including the actual purchase price of the product).
I am seeking help, but Stripe support just tells me it is not working.
This could be a vulnerability of Stripe, if your competitor uses Stripe and you want to destroy the competitor's payment system, just test the stolen credit card like crazy and obviously your competitor's Stripe account will be closed.

Ask HN: Cybersecurity for Elderly Family Members
text:
What are your tips & advice to protect elderly family members from ransomware/ phishing scams/ malware pop ups?

ie. I am thinking about putting their home routers behind NextDNS that can be managed passively/remotely.

Many email security tools (ie. Proofpoint) are not commonly available to consumers, but can be very helpful for the elderly. Obviously, there’s some effort to regularly maintain the setup.
